segments.text: We are in the Planning Department of the City of Houston, and I'm interviewing Johnny Rea.
Johnny, how do you spell your last name?
R-A-I-A.
R-A-I-A.
How long have you been with the Planning Department?

I've been here since, well I've gone and come back, I've been here over 30 years but there was a period that I left from 56 to 58 and went out into the private sector and I worked with an engineer and my training was in architecture and I wanted to get into that and unfortunately I left at kind of a bad time economic wise and so I came back to the planning department and I've been here ever since.
When did you join the Planning Department?
What year was that?
It was in 55.
And that was under which name?
Ralph Elliford.
Ralph Elliford.
I served under every director we had because Ralph was the first.
Mr. Elliford was replaced by whom?
Roscoe Jones.
Roscoe.
And then, of course, we have Mr. Garcia now.
What have been your assignments in the department?

Well, I started out in the drafting section, hosting subdivisions, and there came a time when we needed to have some public information, a person that could handle the public and interface with the engineers and the realtors and the public and the whole spectrum.
So I was very much interested in that, so I took that.
And I've had the public information section since then.
Let me just stop this one.
So you've been dealing with the public for quite a few years.
How long has that been?
Well, I left in 56.
I went to work as an engineer.
And actually, we were doing a lot of apartment building.
It was really the rational apartments that were just beginning in Houston.
And then we hit a period of, they call it, an economic recession.
More like a depression than a recession.
And so business was kind of rough.
And at that time, there was some changes happening in the planning department.
What kind of changes?

Well, the assistant director, Fernando Williams, he and one of the planners, they're now Williams and Crawford, but it was Fernando Williams and Harold Crawford, they were forming their own company and they left.
And so there was just sort of a rearranging of new people being hired in the department.
So I came back.
And that's when we really specifically set up a public information section.
And it was just sort of a realignment of duties within the planning department.
And I've been handling that ever since.
And there were times, of course, that was a growing period.

And there was just constant information of realtors coming in for their clients, the clients coming in, and engineers coming in and checking on subdivisions and widenings, and the whole planning process as it was operating then.
It was just handling the public for that period.
Well, you've observed several styles of planning under the three directors.
Could you characterize those different styles of planning?
and the role of the department?
Oh, sure.
I would say under Mr. Elford, it was just the beginnings, the concepts, and the major thoroughfare as we know it today was born with him.
That's when he was formally presented, and he laid the groundwork for the entire
as we know it now, and I deal with major thoroughfares all the time, so that's sort of like the reference point.
And then Mr. Jones continued it, and of course Mr. Garcia is going into a different phase because he's incorporating a different concept.
They're going into a comprehensive plan, and I might say that before we did a subdivision doing Mr. Jones's,
Well, Mr. Elliford was just in the sharp stand of Westbury, and all of those were coming in.
And then he left in 1963, and the building had already started.
And then he started.
It was just a continuous flow of subdivisions, and we just had a fantastic amount of subdivisions that went from doing that to Mr. Johnson's period.
That was about the time that Vernon Henry left.
the department and open his own practice?
Vernon Henry was active.
He was a subdivision planner and he also was when we had the zoning effort.
We had a zoning effort here and he worked with a planner in that section.
It was called Otto Krebs.
Otto Krebs.
He's since passed away.
But they had the big zoning effort and that failed and he left pretty soon after that.
and started his own office.
I think he was with Newhouse and Taylor first, and then he formed his own office.
You've probably talked to him since.
Yes.
And Mary Lou.
And Mary Lou.
And she worked here too.
I think that's where they met, isn't it?
It was an office romance.
Well, not exactly at first, but I guess you could say it evolved.
Evolved, yeah.
Okay.
Ross goes...
view of the role of planning in Houston I think was quite different than Ralph's.
I would say he wasn't here at the beginning, so I think he pretty much followed the groundwork that was laid with the authority that he had.
Which was apparently quite limited.
Was Ralph's authority so limited?
Oh, when you're beginning something, I would imagine everyone is, well, I'll use the Major Thurford as a good example.
If it wasn't anything that, of course we had a skeleton out on the front, but he was the one that formalized it and had a major, which is what we were using as our Bible, pretty much.
So if you're starting something, then by sheer necessity, you're starting it.
Mm-hmm.

Then, of course, there were variations on the theme and different alignments, but it was pretty much the Planning Commission was sort of using that as the groundwork and was sort of carrying through a concept that was born, Mr. Elford, born with Mr. Elford and carried on by Mr. Jones, because it had already been laid out and the construction and the planning had started using the developers as they presented their plans and got them processed through the Planning Commission.
Has the succession of mayors made any impact on the practice of planning in Houston that you can characterize?
I would say this, in Whitmer's administration, well, Mr. Garcia has a complete set of authority as it stands now.
He's gone into a number of things that
I don't think we're here doing Mr. Johnson's administration.
This is a whole different concept.
He has the mayor behind him in everything that he does.
Are you suggesting that this hasn't always been the case?
Oh, well, of course not.
works at, serves at the pleasure of the mayor.
So it's just that you have a different, you have a person now that seems to have brought Mr. Garcia in to do a planning, even changed the name of the department before it was city planning.
And that's called planning and development, which means that it's one of the most significant changes, I would say, is this development process.
I've been working a little with that, too.
And that's where we get a chance to look at the construction where we didn't before.
The main thrust of a development plant is a setback.
And that was evolved because we had a major thoroughfare.
Woodway is a major thoroughfare.
We didn't have any setback lines.
If we had widening, it was precisely for the waterway and suggested setback lines.
Now, with the development plants, you have a firm 10-foot setback on a local street, a 25-foot setback on a major thoroughfare.
Woodway has some tremendous office buildings that are built right on the property line.
We asked them, suggested setting it back.
They said, we can legally do this, so they've done it.
And so now we have what is referred to as Woodway Canyon, because if you drive along the street, you'll see that these buildings, you have the sensation they're falling in on the river.
That's quite ironic.
So this is a good concept.
That's quite ironic, because that's the neighborhood that Ralph Elliford lives in.
But see, back then, we didn't have the authority for setback lines.
We had four, and there was a tremendous- When did that happen, that the authority was given to you?
Oh, it was 82.
Now, with Mr. Elliford, he did the, like I say, the major thoroughfare plan was laid out.
Then we had an end one.
When I came into the department, we were doing what were called alignment studies, where we were taking the major thoroughfares and actually designing the widening, going-

say taking aerial photographs, taking base maps, going out in the field and picking the most economical route to lay out and coming back in, making an alignment, presenting it to the mayor, approved by council.
Who was the mayor then?
When I first came in, it was Couture.
And then there was a succession.
He served under a number of mayors for 20 years.
And that was really good.
a large part of the operation with the alignment studies.
And that's the, continued that process after it was, the mayor and council approved it.
It went to the permit office and they literally held back a building.
They have the authority to hold back the building
from within those right-of-way lines that we had proposed.
It was sort of like an official plan line then.
Well, it was, sure.
That kept the corridor free.
Right, but that was as far as the corridor, but no setbacks.
No setbacks.
We had suggested setbacks, but there's no way to say
they could build right on the proposed, up to that point, building lines that was known were there.
Normally, setback, side and rear and front yard setbacks are included in a subdivision, I think.
Yes, now that's usually the interior lot lines and the rear property lines are handled by the permit office.
But these were the setback lines on the, between the public right-of-way
and the private property.
And that was the main, at least we had that as a tool until we got the development plan.
Of course, in subdivisions, we did have a full range of setbacks for your subdivisions, depending on whether it was residential.
Residential even had a further setback than we use now.
It was a 35-foot setback off of a major thoroughfare.
And then they'd have 25-foot setbacks off of your local streets.
That was in a residential.
And of course, they could set back further.
We have a number of rural subdivisions where they even have as much as 50 and 75-foot setbacks back when they thought that it was going to be out in the country.
And unfortunately, the country now is part of the city.
So they're trying to get those setback lines changed around people in that area so they can use that property.
I don't know if that's, I guess that's in business because it showed a thinking of a subdivision back at that time.
Have you noticed any change in the structure of the department itself?
Oh, yes.
How has that changed through the years?
Well, through the years from alignment studies.
Because you've been here the longest of anyone.
And so I'm relying on your memory in terms of the dynamics of the organization.
Well, I'd say, as I've mentioned, the alignment studies were really the important things.
When the subdivisions weren't, you know, there just weren't that many.
They were here, and we were guiding them as it happened.
But then I would say the...
that's when it started picking up with the tremendous development that we've had.

So the importance shifted from the alignment studies, which are now laid out, so it actually came along at the right time, because we had actually had a chance to lay out all of the alignment and the major third figures.
so the developers could then, when they designed their subdivisions, they were aware that they had to dedicate the right of way for major thoroughfares.
So then it shifted from alignment studies to these subdivisions that were actually developing the land.
And of course now the subdivisions have sort of, because of the economy, we don't have the volume
of subdivisions that we've had back when, say, Mr. Jones was here.
He was here at the peak of the development, our subdivision development, I would say.
And so now we're getting into the comprehensive plan where we're going now into neighborhoods are being stressed more than they were.
And you're doing it by sectors, aren't you, or quarters or whatever?
Just announced yesterday.
And of course, in the past, we've had, they're called sectors now, but we've had
under the other directors.
So they were called planning units, planning areas, neighborhood studies.
But now I think he's getting it into a formalized
set of land areas that we can look at and just go into the studies in-depth.
Money has a lot to do with that, too.
Maybe we're getting a little more money for these studies that we've never had before.
I guess when things got breakneck speed with subdivisions, I guess we were assuming we were pushing out and we weren't thinking of the interior in it.
the interior neighborhoods take care of themselves.
But that's the difference, I would say, in the mayors, is that you've got a mayor now that's very much interested in the interior neighborhoods.
Well, I think that's interesting in terms of the current economy and in terms of transportation.
Certainly, Houston is not a joy to commute in.
And that brings up the topic of Metro.
Would you like to prepare to comment on Metro at all?
Well, Metro, there's a need for it this year, and it's a thousand percent better than what we've had in the past.
I mean, at least you've got bus routes now that you can rely on.
There seems to be some tremendous leadership.
From my impression, they're also getting into the...
some of the repair of streets and some of the things from their monies that they're getting through the one percent sales tax.
One percent.
Everybody keeps thinking it's one cent, but it's one percent.
They're getting charged tremendously.
I would say more than the city of Houston would because when it was, we were the ones that actually did the beginning of Metro.
And it was a unique thing.
It was...

the county was divided into five parts, and so they knew that the whole county wasn't, maybe there might be a different number, so they divided it into five parts to see which areas would be interested, and as it was voted on, four parts voted for it, one part voted against it, and they chose not to be in it.
I don't know if you know this or not.
No.
But the eastern part of Harris County, say from US 59, East Texas Freeway,
around to the Gulf Freeway, which are all the smaller cities of Winter Park, December City, and those cities chose not to participate in Metro.
So they do not collect the 1% sales tax.
So what you've got is all the north and west areas that are, that's where all your money from Metro is coming from.
It's kind of a unique thing.
I thought we were taking less than a unit to do this.
Frateras County is a pretty big county as they go in Texas.
When the city attempted to do this, then the bond issue failed, as I recall, and that was something of a setback.
But then Metro was reorganized under a separate administration, and then they were able to move independently of city administration, which
probably turned out to be a good thing.
Yes, I mean, because they had a different priority.
But the way we interface now.
Excuse me, are you Mr.
I was going to say they have a set of, but the interface with the city is the fact that they are now taking some of their monies for the repair streets.
And they're taking the parking lot lots and that seems to be a successful operation also where people are willing to get out of their cars.
Well, actually, they get in their cars, park them, whatever, and then take their ride into town.
It's an interesting concept.
I guess it's been done all over the nation, but it's the first time in Israel we've ever done it.
That's a new concept, and it seems to be working out pretty good.
And then the Highway Department has cooperated in terms of bus lanes and whatnot.
Now that's another concept that Metro started.
And it seems to me, except for the people that are in the cars, I'll add that.
I get the complaints from them that some people say that that's taking something away from the...
from the automobile, but we've got to live together.
If this can carry a lot of traffic and a lot of people to a destination, then so be it.
We've got to work.
That's part of the implementation of the plan.
And we're still using the major thoroughfare plan that was laid back by Mr. Olford years ago.
And the more I see it, the more I think it's brilliant the way he did it.

The major change that you've mentioned seems to be a change in terms of the attention of the planning department moving away from the periphery and concentrating more on infill and more on the needs of commuter traffic.
and mass transit.
And actually, I don't know if you can say that the Central Business District is as important as it was back then.
It seemed like when ASAP first came in, the Central Business District was the main thing.
And it seemed like we did early subdivision studies before the, that might be another thing I want to add, that we were doing subdivision studies back,
when there wasn't as many subdivisions coming in.
And the stress was on single-family residential.
It was supposed to be that way.
And as things at Breakneck Street got more and more, we didn't do the studies as much as coordinating
and giving the engineer a chance to do the design of his particular subdivision and thus coordinating it with the overall major thoroughfare network.
That's kind of a different attitude also.
But in doing the subdivision's design and the engineer feeling that he had to pretty much conform to that design, it was left up to him.
to just to interface with a sort of like a guide rather than a controller.

Maybe I'm using a little bit of diplomatic language, but rather than us designing a subdivision for someone here, an engineer feeling compelled to use that design, Mr. Jones said let the engineer design it and we coordinate it with our overall plan.
So that was a little bit of a different kind of thing.
The lead now is probably being taken a little bit more by the department.
It sounds like there's a much firmer control and much more enthusiastic applying of rules and regulations.
Johnny, are there any comments that you'd like to summarize with?

Well, I've enjoyed the department and enjoyed my, as I say, my expertise is in public information, and I thought it would be over, but there seems to be, the more we go, the more the public needs to be informed.
And this is one thing for my standpoint, is
I find that explaining to a person, any individual, even when they haven't conformed to the rules and regulations, if you explain it to them reasonably, they seem to understand.
And it's an educational process.
There's one thing I'd like to ask you.
If you know of any documents that I can use in writing the history of planning in Houston, that might be important.
If you could get those together for me, I would very much appreciate it.
And I can return them.
We've got some things here that I hand out to people constantly that come in from out of state.
Out of the city, but out of state because of our unique no zoning.
So there's some information.
We have some papers that Mr. Jones had a paper on non-zoning in Houston.
And then there was an attorney that Mr. Olson,
That was the city attorney here that had a speech that he seemed to cover pretty well.
The district said it's an alternate to zoning.
And there was an architect that, from his standpoint, I'll get that for you also.
OK.
I'm going to be here probably till about 3 this afternoon.
So maybe I could drop back after.
Sure.
I've enjoyed it very much.
Thank you very much.
The same day, we're in the office of Ephraim Garcia, the Planning Director for the Department of Planning and Development for the City of Houston.
Ephraim, you came from San Antonio.
That's correct.
You worked for Winston-Martin.
Winston-Martin, the San Antonio Development Agency.
What was your responsibility in San Antonio with Winston?
I was the manager of the project
Planning and Management Division.
We planned the various projects and then managed them after they were funded.
These involved neighborhood redevelopment projects, downtown redevelopment projects, all the activities of the development agency.
That development agency is somewhat unusual in Texas, isn't it?
Well, I think it's somewhat unusual nationally in that the urban renewal projects that were handled by that division have been successful throughout that agency.
And so that in San Antonio, the urban renewal program is pointed out as a successful program, where in many cities in the country, it was an unsuccessful program.
Then you got the call from Houston.
That's right.
When was that?
How did that happen?
Would you describe the circumstances and the date?
In November of 1982, I received a call from a member of the mayor's staff asking me to submit a resume, that they were looking for a planning director and I had been recommended.
At that time, they didn't indicate who I had been recommended by.
So I was not particularly over enthused with coming to Houston, but I did send them a resume.
And I didn't hear anything from them from that date until Christmas.
A week after Christmas in 1982, I received a call.
Could I come up and meet Kathy Whitmire and talk to her about the position?
So I came up here, and I had about a two or three hour conversation with her.
Left and went back home.
And the next day, they called me up and said that they were prepared to offer me the position.
Two or three hours is a long interview.
You're right.
We went over a lot of...
It must have been serious.
And I wasn't quite that sure that I wanted to come up because there was a lot of things going on in San Antonio.
I was thinking of going into the consulting business and phasing out of the San Antonio Development Agency and so forth.
And so I rejected the job offer and said that I was not interested.
Then...

I began to get telephone calls from various people, from Councilman Ben Reyes, indicating that they had been pushing Kathy Whitmire to get Hispanic department directors, and I was the first one, and that I was qualified, and I was turning them down.
And then there's a phone call...
We were at the point where I turned the job down, and so I began to receive certain phone calls from Houston people asking me to take the job.
Then Kathy Hoodmeyer called and asked me to come up again for another interview.
Now, what I found out had happened is that they had, when I turned the job down, they went out to various planning consultants and people here and asked for recommendations for a planning director.
not telling them that I had turned the job down.
And when the recommendations came in again, my name was at the head of those recommendations.
So they decided to make a renewed effort to get me to.
And so by then, with the second interview, I knew that I was kind of in a negotiating position now.
So we began negotiating as to what was involved.
We arrived at a consensus that if I took the job, I would be given the free hand in reorganizing the department, that the personnel would be provided that I needed, that I could integrate.

Since my primary efforts in San Antonio had been redevelopment, and I was very interested in that, that economic development and redevelopment would be made a part of the department instead of separate divisions.
And also that the computer system that the city was introducing, the Metricon computer system, would be assigned to the department.
At that time, I thought it was a plus.
I found out it was a liability afterwards.
And so we arrived at an idea that if I took over, I would basically be given a free hand in the department, that she was ready for planning, that she was ready for initiating redevelopment.
that prior mayors had ignored redevelopment entirely.
Houston was a new construction town, and you always went out and built on the edge of town instead of trying to redevelop the inner city neighborhoods.
And since a large part of her constituency was minority, she wanted to do something about inner city neighborhoods.
And the thing that really convinced me was the fact that
The development ordinance had just been passed, and she wanted someone to begin to implement the development ordinance, which are the first set of development controls.
And so I agreed to take the job, so I came to work here on the 1st of March.

Afterwards, I found out that what had happened is Kathy had gone down to San Antonio shortly after her election and spent four days down there going over the projects that the San Antonio Development Agency, the redevelopment projects that the San Antonio Development Agency was doing, and looking at that, and then had asked Henry Cisneros to recommend someone that could
come from San Antonio Hill to do the same type of work, and that he had recommended me.
I didn't know what prompted the call for my resume.
I found that out later.
Interesting.
Very interesting.
So this is quite a change, then, in terms of the structure of the Planning and Development Department.
Its name has changed, the structure of it has changed, you have added responsibilities now, and I understand that the
support, the decision-making support for the planning function is much stronger than it used to be.
Yes.
What has happened, first of all, in numbers, the department has gone from 62 to 150.
How long did it take to do that?
It took about three years.
Because we did it gradually.
Secondly, the management structure
has been changed completely.
One of the big problems that I found when I arrived here was that the planning director was isolated.
He had one secretary, and that was the entire set of his staff.
Then everything was done at the division level.
There was no assistant director.
That position had been vacant for several months.
And there was a division manager that was functioning as the Kerry Gilbert was functioning as the
Assistant Director, and then, of course, once my appointment was announced, which was about a two or three month period, then the prior director left.
And so there was a gap.
Roscoe left.
Roscoe left.
He was on leave, actually, but he left.
And so that Kerry was running the department when I got here.
And I found myself very severely handicapped initially with a lack of an administrative support staffer for the director.
It was myself and the secretary, and that was it.
And the next step down was operating divisions.
For a city like Houston.
Yes.
And when I asked the reason for this, I don't want to talk about someone else, but I was told that someone that only got three or four phone calls a week, that was sufficient staff to support him.
And so the...
And as I began expanding the department, I did not want to initially start building my staff.
So it was a very difficult and slow process to get the adequate support staff.
But now we have a well-organized, what I think is actually I think the ideal organization for a planning department in the country.
Because we not only have the means of preparing plans,
But we also have the means of implementing those.
We have charge of the Community Development Block Grant Program and that budget.
I'm a member of the CIP committee that selects the CIP projects.
I am in charge of a committee that we call the Joint Referral Committee that handles all matters that relate to more than one department of the city.
the Public Works Department, the Traffic and Transportation and Real Estate Department.
Those are usually matters dealing with real estate, streets, acquisition, closing of streets, and selling of city property, and so forth, and acquiring city property.
Do you have anything to do with the annual budget, aside from the departmental budget?
The only annual budget that we deal with is the annual budget for community development.
That's a $20 to $25 million budget that we prepare entirely here in the department.

But other than that, I only participate indirectly in the annual budget in that as part of the CIP committee, we then select the projects that need to be done that indirectly then establish a requirement for bond sales
which then established the requirement for debt service in that particular year's bond issue.
And now in the period of shortfall, that has become a rather important aspect of planning, that securing and selecting the right projects.
Because we're looking now at projects, for example, that
do not require staffing after they're constructed.
So we're deferring, let's say, a multi-service center as opposed to building streets.
We can build streets, and those don't require any additional maintenance or staffing.
But if we built a multi-service center, then we would have to hire the people to staff it.
And that would increase the operating costs, would then add to the budget.
So we do those type of decisions, but I do it as part of the CIP committee rather than.
And the CIP committee is composed of the director of public works, director of finance,
myself, and the representative of the mayor's office.
So it's a fairly small, powerful committee.
Yes.
And historically, we're in the third year of our CIP program.
It started the first year that I got here.
And we have succeeded in getting the city council to approve the CIP prepared by this committee with only very, very minor changes.
And I think last year there was only one project that was changed.
Even though we have abandoned the prior system in Houston of dividing capital improvements to each council district, whether they needed them or not, everybody got their fair share.
And now we're using a priority system, which means that last year, for example, on this current bond issue, one district got 28% of the money.
and one district got 5% of the money.
That disparity, and yet the city council approved the plan unanimously.
So they have basically bought our process as being a good process.
That's quite a change from previous years.
Ephraim, recently you've been taking a little political heat.
And I understand you've written an article that appeared in the Houston Business News?
That was an interview.
An interview.
And I understand it was quite a good article that was published, and I'd like to pick up a copy of that.
Would you like to comment on how this political heat was generated, and by whom, and how you're responding to it?
Well, the political heat had to do with the Community Development Block Grant Program.
What I did is, in October of 84, the last major element that was added to the department was the community development division.
And Houston has had a troubled community development program.
And when I took over...
It was not only troubled, but there was some... Scandal, and there's been some convictions, and so forth.
And so I was handed a program that had a backlog of $90 million of unspent money, primarily in capital improvements projects.
And from that date, October 84, when I took over the program, there was $1 million of construction.
To date, we have been able to construct $52 million worth of projects.
And that involved having to go out and engineer, design projects, and get them built.
So we've made considerable progress over these last two years.

Unfortunately, the Department of Housing and Urban Development chose this year, when all the progress is finally occurring, to penalize Houston for the prior 12 years of malfeasance and mismanagement.
And so that's caused a political problem, because the implication is, even though HUD is saying, we're doing this because in all the 12 years of the history of the program, Houston has never spent
their full share of money, this is the year they decided to do something about it.

And so the impression that has been left with some of the council members and what the media has given everyone is that mismanagement is still occurring in the system, even though all the HUD reports now indicate that we're doing well.
And the mayor and I have been meeting with the HUD people trying to
have them overturn that penalty, which was they penalized us by taking $2.6 million of our community development block.
The impression the media gives is that the planning department is sitting on their hands and not spending the money that they have available.
No, the money is being spent.
In fact, this year HUD established a goal of $37 million for us to spend, which is almost twice of our annual allocation, and we actually will spend over $40 million.
and we'll exceed the HUD goal by $3 million.
And that is the argument we're making to HUD, is we're exceeding the goal.
Why penalize, why select this year to be the penalty year?
And of course, they're pointing out the fact that for 12 years, they have been given priority goals, and they have never been met.
And they have got to understand that the structure has changed now.
Well, and just yesterday, I received the annual monitoring report, and they compliment us
on all the management changes and et cetera.
But of course, they're sticking to their decision to take the $2.6 million as justified because they could have taken as much as $10 to $20 million if they had implemented that several years ago.
So they're telling us, you're lucky that we didn't do it then and waited till now because we only took $2.6.
But that's cause for some bad relations with city council members because they don't understand the situation.
So they want to know from you why it hasn't been spent.
Right.
But you can give them answers.
Do they seem to be understanding this?
Well, the form of government here in Houston is almost identical to the federal system.
You have the mayor, who represents the administration.
She appoints the department directors.
And then you have the city council, which sits there as the legislative body and is
continuously at ends with the mayor, at odds with the mayor.
And so therefore, even though the council members understand, they still make out like they don't understand because they get at the mayor by criticizing her department directors.
